"Brentrup F., Küsters J., Kuhlmann H., Lammel J.","Application of the Life Cycle Assessment methodology to agricultural production: An example of sugar beet production with different forms of nitrogen fertilisers",2001,"European Journal of Agronomy","14","3",,"221","233",,,10.1016/S1161-0301(00)00098-8,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035007369&partnerID=40&md5=e9bb4485efd34ef0f624aaafb125b3c3","Centre for Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof, Hydro Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof 35, Hanninghof 35, 48249 Duelmen, Germany","Brentrup, F., Centre for Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof, Hydro Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof 35, Hanninghof 35, 48249 Duelmen, Germany; Küsters, J., Centre for Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof, Hydro Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof 35, Hanninghof 35, 48249 Duelmen, Germany; Kuhlmann, H., Centre for Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof, Hydro Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof 35, Hanninghof 35, 48249 Duelmen, Germany; Lammel, J., Centre for Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof, Hydro Plant Nutrition, Hanninghof 35, Hanninghof 35, 48249 Duelmen, Germany","The suitability of the Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) methodology to analyse the environmental impact of agricultural production is investigated. The first part of an LCA is an inventory of all the resources used and emissions released due to the system under investigation. In the following step, i.e. the Life Cycle Impact Assessment the inventory data were analysed and aggregated in order to finally get one index representing the total environmental burden. For the Life Cycle Impact Assessment (LCIA) the Eco-indicator 95 method has been chosen, because this is a well-documented and regularly applied impact assessment method. The resulting index is called Eco-indicator value. The higher the Eco-indicator value the stronger is the total environmental impact of an analysed system. A sugar beet field experiment conducted in northeastern Germany was chosen as an example for the analysis. In this experiment three different nitrogen fertilisers (calcium ammonium nitrate = CAN, urea ammonium nitrate solution = UAN, urea) were used at optimum N rates. The obtained Eco-indicator values were clearly different for the N fertilisers used in the sugar beet trial. The highest value was observed for the system where urea was used as N source. The lowest Eco-indicator value has been calculated for the CAN system. The differences are mainly due to different ammonia volatilisation after application of the N fertilisers. For all the systems the environmental effects of acidification and eutrophication contributed most to the total Eco-indicator value. The results show that the LCA methodology, is basically suitable to assess the environmental impact associated with agricultural production. A comparative analysis of the system's contribution to global warming, acidification, eutrophication and summer smog is possible. However, some important environmental issues are missing in the Eco-indicator 95 method (e.g. the use of resources and land). © 2001 Elsevier Science B.V.","Eco-indicator 95; Environmental impact; LCA; Life cycle assessment; Nitrogen fertiliser; Sugar beet","agricultural production; environmental impact assessment; fertilizer application; nitrogen",,,,,,"Andersson, K., Ohlsson, T., Life Cycle Assessment of bread produced on different scales (1999) Int. J. LCA, 4, pp. 25-40; Audsley, E., Harmonisation of Environmental Life Cycle assessment for agriculture (1997) Final Report. Concerted Action MR3-CT94-2028, , Silsoe Research Institute, Silsoe; Bach, M., Becker, R., (1995) Regional differenzierte Abschätzung des Nitrateintrages aus diffusen Quellen in das Grundwasser - Untersuchung flir die Bundesrepublik, , Institut für Landeskultur, University of Gießen; Bouwman, A.F., (1995) Compilation of a global inventory of emissions of nitrous oxide, , Ph.D. thesis, University of Wageningen; Braunschweig, A., Förster, R., Hofstetter, P., Müller-Wenk, R., (1996) IWÖ-Diskussionsbeitrag, 32. , Developments in L